  {
    "name": "ED - Mod Manual",
    "civilopediaText": [
      {
        "text": "Emperors and Deities is an overhaul mod for Sid Meier's Civilization 5/Unciv."
      },
      {
        "text": "The mod's main goal is to reshape Civ 5 into a more complex and nuanced game with many new mechanics incorporated.\nMajor Differences:"
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "1. Keep in mind that Luxury Resources no longer provide any [Happiness] by default; they provide a large amount of [Gold] and development potential. However, 'We Love the King Day' and city-state quests still require Luxury Resources. As for how you gain [Happiness], you can build many buildings and create a religion with suitable beliefs."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "2. Armies are now separated into four major categories:\n 'Levy Army', 'Standing Army', 'Noble Army' and 'Mercenary Army', each with different characteristics."
      },
      {
        "text": "In other words, you cannot build a powerful army without building ['Military Building']s like [Barracks] to increase the unit limit."
      },
      {
        "text": "For a more in-depth explanation",
        "link": "Tutorial/ED - Reworked Army Mechanic"
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "3. The tag system is used widely in this mod. A tag is a word surrounded by '', and many mechanics revolve around this system. They are also in the civilopedia of any object, so feel free to check. You don't need to remember this well to use it effectively as most tags are intuitive."
      },
      {
        "text": "For a more in-depth explanation",
        "link": "Tutorial/ED - Tags"
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "4. [Influence] is a new currency that affects the political status of your civilization, limited by [Influence Limit]. You get it by keeping [Happiness] positive, choosing the right policies, and through [Enact Policies] decisions. If your [Influence] is negative, you will get a negative event that lowers stability, which provides huge debuffs. You can check the civilopedia page of [Influence] for more information."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Back to the tutorial menu",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Tutorial Menu"
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "See also: Influence",
        "link": "Resources/Influence"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: ED - Stability and Events",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Stability and Events"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "ED - Starting Tips & Where to Settle",
    "civilopediaText": [
      {
        "text": "When starting a new game, remember to switch to Neolithic Era if you want to build your civ from the ground up. Since Unciv defaults to Ancient Era, you might lose some content there or find some progress you didn't intend to have, like government forms being different."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "When starting a new game in Neolithic Era or Ancient Era, you would likely have two types of units: [Hunter Gatherer]s and [Settler]s."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "The major difference between Civ 5/Unciv and this mod is that your starting unit, the [Hunter Gatherer], is not only a ranged unit but also a worker that can build [Camp]s, [Manual Farm]s, and [Manual Plantation]s. However, it cannot upgrade to other units. They represent humanity's earliest endeavor at building civilizations."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "As for [Settler]s, there are no major differences, but note that settling near [River]s gives 2 extra [Food] and an extra 1 [Food] near [Lakes]. These don't stack but provide a strong starting bonus for your cities."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "With [Road Network], [Settler]s also gain +1 [Movement] on [Open terrain] after researching [Horse Collar] technology with [Cart] promotion. Neat upgrades like this exist in many places in this mod, so you should take a proper look at each option you're given."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "When looking for a place to settle, luxury resources do give you a lot of [Gold] and other stats but are no longer a source of [Happiness]. Maintaining a balance between [Production]-giving resources like [Minerals] and [Clay], [Food] terrains like [Black Soil] and [Lakes], and [Food] resources like [Grain] and [Caprinae] makes your new cities much more useful. It is also important that you can do [Canal Construction] to connect your inland cities to the sea. And [Mountain]-requiring buildings like [Observatory] no longer require settling beside [Mountain]s; a 2-tile distance is also good enough."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Back to the tutorial menu",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Tutorial Menu"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "ED - Stability and Events",
    "civilopediaText": [
      {
        "text": "The original Unciv/Civ 5 offers a flat debuff when the empire is unhappy, but Emperors and Deities turned the flat debuff into instability and negative events. Negative events often interact with variables like the number of cities or what Era you are in. To cure the debuff from them, you can check out options in [Enact Policies] or in the building tab."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "[Chaos Ensue] is an event that lowers your stability. It occurs if you are lacking [Happiness] (going negative). It also occurs more frequently in [Unified] states. You will need to choose between spending some [Influence] and [Gold] to prevent it or having your stability lowered. This disables some abilities like building workers when you are in a state of [Strife]."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "To keep [Chaos Ensue] from occurring, you will need to keep your [Happiness] and [Influence] higher than normal, which is not ideal. So it is a risk you will always face. Remember to always keep some spare [Gold] and [Influence]."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "[Wealth Gap Widens], [Rampant Corruption], and [Vagrancy Crisis] are events that only occur when you are lacking [Happiness]. They may apply debuffs to all the cities you own, which can be a nightmare to deal with."
      },
      {
        "text": "Luckily, you can use your capital to deal with them. Unluckily, your capitals are limited, so do what you can to prevent the lack of [Happiness]."
      },
      {
        "text": "The Events Listed Above are only examples of what could be possible. But remember, when a event occur, as long as you have enough [Influence] and [Gold] as safety net, you will endure. And there are even sometimes benefits from the negative events."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Back to the tutorial menu",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Tutorial Menu"
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "See also: Peace",
        "link": "Buildings/Peace"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Struggle",
        "link": "Buildings/Struggle"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Strife",
        "link": "Buildings/Strife"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Anarchy",
        "link": "Buildings/Anarchy"
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Slum",
        "link": "Buildings/Slum"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Unjust Ruling",
        "link": "Buildings/Unjust Ruling"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Peasant Rebellion",
        "link": "Buildings/Peasant Rebellion"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Remove Slums",
        "link": "Buildings/Remove Slums"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Clear Corruption",
        "link": "Buildings/Clear Corruption"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Stop Rebellion",
        "link": "Buildings/Stop Rebellion"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "ED - Government Forms",
    "civilopediaText": [
      {
        "text": "(This mechanic does exist in BNW, but the author of this mod never copied that.)"
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Government forms like [Tribes] and [Tribal Union] are the first examples of government forms you might encounter."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "A government form provides army limits like [Standing Army Maintenance], [Influence Limit]s, and unique bonuses. For [Tribes], it's a discount for policies. For [Tribal Union], it's a growth bonus and a chance to evolve into [Early Empire] in the Ancient Era through reforms."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "There are two types of government forms: ['United'] and ['Divided']. ['United'] government forms have cheaper National Wonders, access to all diplomatic actions, and powerful uniques. Many historically significant empires belong to this category, like [SPQR] and [Great Qin]."
      },
      {
        "text": "On the other hand, it doesn't mean ['Divided'] government forms are definitely weaker. They fit into their own niche by having cheaper policy costs, access to ['Agreement'] via [Enact Policies], and generally taking less effort to maintain."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "The most convenient way to change your government form is to let it naturally evolve. When each Era begins, you are forced to have a political shift where you must actively decide what state you want to enter: ['United'] or ['Divided']."
      },
      {
        "text": "You can also force a political shift by having your [Influence] go above the [Influence Limit] or reform a ['United'] government form when your [Influence] is at half or above the [Influence Limit]."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "To keep a government form during a [Shift in politic] event, you would need to keep your [Influence] above 3/4 of the [Influence Limit]."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "['United'] government forms are gated behind the requirement of having enough [Happiness] and [Influence]. You need to have your [Influence] reach half of the [Influence Limit] and your empire being happy."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Back to the tutorial menu",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Tutorial Menu"
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "List of all possible government forms",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Available Civilization Forms of different eras"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "ED - Reworked Army Mechanic",
    "civilopediaText": [
      {
        "text": "Armies are now separated into four major categories:\n 'Levy Army', 'Standing Army', 'Noble Army', and 'Mercenary Army', each with different characteristics."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "'Levy Army' units are free and can be summoned using the [Call to Arms] function in any city with five or more population at the cost of [Happiness] and short-term negative effects. The [Call to Arms] status can be reverted by disbanding your levies in peaceful times using [Enact Policies] at the capital so they can be summoned again."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "'Standing Army', 'Noble Army', and 'Mercenary Army' behave like normal units, except 'Mercenary Army' can only be bought and requires a [Mercenary Office] to be built. 'Standing Army' and its elite variant 'Noble Army' are what you would rely upon most of the time; however, they do require resources like [Iron] and [Weapon Parts] to be built."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "The main source of [Standing Army Maintenance] is government forms and ['Military Building']s."
      },
      {
        "text": "The main source of [Noble Army Maintenance] is government forms and policies."
      },
      {
        "text": "The main source of [Mercenary Contract] is ['Economic Building']s and city-states."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Back to the tutorial menu",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Tutorial Menu"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "ED - Tags",
    "civilopediaText": [
      {
        "text": "There are many tags for different buildings, resources, and units."
      },
      {
        "text": "It is mostly a system for implementing strengths and weaknesses in terms of units, but for resources and buildings, it's a system that applies many buffs."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "So you need to play with tags in mind. For example, when [Early Mobilization] from [Militant] gives you a bonus on constructing ['Static Defense'], you can build more [Walls]. And later adopt [Knighthood] from [Feudalism] to give them [Culture] production."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "This is a system that doesn't require overthinking. Normally, you just need to pay some attention to what you are doing, and the tag system will reward you accordingly."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "All building sorted by type tags",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Buildings by Tag"
      },
      {
        "text": "All units sorted by army tags",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Units by Tag"
      },
      {
        "text": "Back to the tutorial menu",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Tutorial Menu"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "ED - Before Industrial Age",
    "civilopediaText": [
      {
        "text": "Before the Industrial Era, the game runs mostly simliar to Civilization 5. You only have to worry about a few newly added features such as [Standing Army Maintenance], [Influence] and various ['Civilization Form']s."
      },
      {
        "text": "[Standing Army Maintenance] and anything that says a unit consumes are unit limits. Later you would have to worry about [Weapon Parts] and so on but right now lets just say unit limit. You would want to build a lot of ['Military Buildings'] to increase your [Standing Army Maintenance] to get more capable unit into field. Instead of those free levied units that are way more fragile. ['Civilization Form'] also provides a lot of unit limits."
      },
      {
        "text": "Before the [Ancient Era], the focus is to gather as much [Food], [Culture] and [Faith] and settle cities in good spots, the ways to gain [Production] was mostly limited."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "However, after the [Ancient Era], the focus on [Happiness] and [Production] become appearent, although there are still few ways to gain [Science], finally in [Imperial Era], you will have plenty of ways to gain [Science]."
      },
      {
        "text": "Back to the tutorial menu",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Tutorial Menu"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "ED - The Industrial Ages",
    "civilopediaText": [
      {
        "text": "Arriving at the Industrial Age, there are a few distinctive new features."
      },
      {
        "text": "['District Construction']s and ['Area Construction']s are new requirments for industries and new buildings."
      },
      {
        "text": "You will have to allocate tiles near your city center to construct new ['Urban Improvement']s if you want a full access to buildings. But if you are willing to make compromises with land, you may settle at only building ['Area Construction']s."
      },
      {
        "text": "['Urban Improvement']s do have their own synergies akin to [Great Improvement]s and are buffed by certain buildings and policies."
      },
      {
        "text": "[Consumption Supply] and [Consumption Demand] are two new parameters you should keep in mind if you want to industrialize your civilization."
      },
      {
        "text": "If [Consumption Supply] outgrows [Consumption Demand] by 3 + Current Number of Cities*2, you will gain [Overproduction], which slows down the construction of new industries but adds some positive effects."
      },
      {
        "text": "If [Consumption Demand] outgrows [Consumption Supply] by 3 + Current Number of Cities*2, you will gain [Underproduction], which speeds up the construction of new industries but adds some negative effects."
      },
      {
        "text": "[Power] is also a new resource you should keep in mind if you want to keep your industries productive."
      },
      {
        "text": "Every industry will consume a certain amount of [Power]. If [Power] is above [0], they will have the full benefit of electricity in cities with [Power Grid], like increased stats and resource production rates."
      },
      {
        "text": "When below [7] [Industry Size], the city switches to [Low Industry Electricity Cost], consuming [6] [Power]."
      },
      {
        "text": "When between [7] to [15] [Industry Size], the city switches to [Medium Industry Electricity Cost], consuming [12] [Power]."
      },
      {
        "text": "When above [15] [Industry Size], the city switches to [High Industry Electricity Cost], consuming [20] [Power]."
      },
      {
        "text": "[Pollution]s and [Pollution Level]s are inevitable if you want to go anywhere in the [Industrial era] and after that point."
      },
      {
        "text": "The main source of [Pollution] are any industry, any tile improvement, those ['Power Building']s that uses ['Fossil Fuel'] and Rapid consumption."
      },
      {
        "text": "When it comes to halting the Pollution, you could intentionially halt building Industries and tile improvements that you dont need. And focus on technologies, [Sustainability] Policy tree and the various ['Renewable Power'] ['Power Building']s."
      },
      {
        "text": "[Pollution Level] will be a great nuisance, at first it simply decrease the growth, but later it spreads to negatively influence your [Happiness], [Culture] and so on. Each [Pollution Level] will get progressively ruinous to the aspect it spreads to."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Back to the tutorial menu",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Tutorial Menu"
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "See also: Consumption Supply",
        "link": "Resources/Consumption Supply"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Consumption Demand",
        "link": "Resources/Consumption Demand"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Overproduction",
        "link": "Buildings/Overproduction"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Underproduction",
        "link": "Buildings/Underproduction"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Power",
        "link": "Resources/Power"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Power Grid",
        "link": "Buildings/Power Grid"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "ED - Invention and Innovations",
    "civilopediaText": [
      {
        "text": "['Invention']s and ['Innovation']s are new buildings that represent minor technological progression and act like mini National Wonders. They enable you to build certain units and buildings or give functionality boosts to existing buildings. They are built faster when other civilizations have already built them, but if you build it first, you are granted a [Gold] and [Science] boost that scales with the Era of the ['Invention'] or ['Innovation']. It is also important to state that there is no gameplay difference between ['Invention']s and ['Innovation']s."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Invention bonus before Industrial Era"
      },
      {
        "text": "100 [Science], 300 [Gold]"
      },
      {
        "text": "[-33]% production cost of ['Invention']s and ['Innovation']s for other civs"
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Invention bonus Stats after Industrial Era"
      },
      {
        "text": "200 [Science], 500 [Gold]"
      },
      {
        "text": "[-50]% production cost of ['Invention']s and ['Innovation']s for other civs"
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Invention bonus after Atomic Era"
      },
      {
        "text": "250 [Science], 750 [Gold]"
      },
      {
        "text": "[-33]% production cost of ['Invention']s and ['Innovation']s for other civs"
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Back to the tutorial menu",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Tutorial Menu"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "ED - Religion Changes",
    "civilopediaText": [
      {
        "text": "At first, religion premise is decided by the three-way choice betwee [Polytheism], [Monotheism] and [Unity]. Although the one standing out is [Monotheism].\nBecause the other two, [Polytheism] seek to maintain a alliance between [Faith] and [Culture], [Unity] is ambiguous toward [faith], but [Monotheism] is the way to go if you want to delve into religion faster than anyone else. They also have a different selection of wonder to build. Avoiding a fair amount of competition."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Then, you have pantheon, which gives plenty of faith according to the terrain. Even [Monotheism] would have to choose a pantheon as it is a spritual step toward the lord."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Beliefs unlocks plenty of things, aside from buildings like [Monastery] and [Pagoda], some also unlocks wonders. They also helps with decreasing the unhappiness from the population. Some of them need specific policies like [Theocracy] to be adopted.\n Follower Beliefs are ability granters. They enable crucial abilities such as using [Faith] to buy stuff.\n Enhancer Beliefs on the other hand, boosts the religion to spread itself better and gives even more bonuses toward various aspects like military and further utilises [Faith]."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Back to the tutorial menu",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Tutorial Menu"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "ED - Great People Changes",
    "civilopediaText": [
      {
        "text": "Great Persons have been changed. For example, [Great General] has been separated into [Great Commander] and [Great Strategist]. [Great Merchant]s and [Great Engineer]s have new unique mechanics like creating [Iconic Brand]s and [War Machine Blueprint]s. Some [Great Improvement]s like [Customs house], [Holy site]s, and [Landmark]s have bonuses on specific tiles."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Back to the tutorial menu",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Tutorial Menu"
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "See also: Great Commander",
        "link": "Units/Great Commander"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: Great Strategist",
        "link": "Units/Great Strategist"
      },
      {
        "text": "See also: War Machine Blueprint",
        "link": "Resources/War Machine Blueprint"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "ED - Expansions, Consolidation and Modernization",
    "civilopediaText": [
      {
        "text": "City development is organized into three tiers of building packages: \"Expansion\", \"Consolidation\", and \"Modernization\"."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "How packages work: Each package lets you build multiple related buildings at once, saving [Production] and ensuring that development becomes easier with tech investment. Packages become available as you progress through eras. For example, [Agricultural Expansion(River)] builds [Watermill], [Windmill], and [Irrigation System] together and is unlocked by [Crop Rotation]."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "\"Expansion\": \nCovers basic buildings which form the foundation of any town. Which are mostly unlocked before [Medieval era]"
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "\"Consolidation\" \nCovers buildings that forms a proper city and make it useful. Which are mostly unlocked starting from [Medieval era] and before [Industrial era]."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "\"Modernization\" \nCovers buildings that makes a city that is considered modernized. Which are mostly unlocked starting from [Industrial era]. You wouldn't live without them in real life."
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Back to the tutorial menu",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Tutorial Menu"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "ED - Credits",
    "civilopediaText": [
      {
        "text": "Tutorial page WIP"
      },
      {
        "separator": true
      },
      {
        "text": "Back to the tutorial menu",
        "link": "Tutorials/ED - Tutorial Menu"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "ED - Global Uniques",
    "civilopediaText": [
      {
        "text": "[-25]% growth for every 10 [Population]."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "[+20]% Unhappiness from Population for every [5] [Population] after [10]."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "[+25]% unhappiness from the number of cities when city count reaches 5's multiple. [+15]% unhappiness from the number of cities when city count reaches 5's multiple + 2."
      },
      {},
      {
        "text": "[-15]% [Production] when unhappy."
      },
